                            <comment id="11626" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Tue, 30 Nov 2004 04:44:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hey, a thing that I haven&apos;t though about for a looong while &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/wink.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; I completely missed the thread on the forum back in August, unfortunately.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That check which excludes global errors sure looks odd; I don&apos;t remember where it came from. I&apos;ve just changed it to simple errors.hasErrors() calls, and the tests still pass. So I&apos;ll commit this, as I really don&apos;t see the point in the current implementation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note that such remaining errors can only occur when using dirty back of dirty forward. If no such dirty page change is allowed, all validation errors for a given page will immediately show that same page again.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="11627" author="sethladd" created="Tue, 30 Nov 2004 04:49:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks again Juergen!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Actually, it can happen when the submit action is the final action.  IIR, when we hit the final page, it checks everything again.  So, if the page previous to final had a global error, it was missed.  You don&apos;t need to dirty back from a dirty forward.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
